{{short description|The third major extended increase in biodiversity in the Phanerozoic}}
The '''Mesozoic–Cenozoic Radiation''' is the third major extended increase in [[biodiversity]] in the [[Phanerozoic]], after the [[Cambrian Explosion]] and the [[Great Ordovician Biodiversification Event]]. The Mesozoic–Cenozoic Radiation began in the mid-[[Mesozoic]] and extends through the [[Cenozoic]], with no indication of having yet ended. It differs from the earlier radiations in that the diversity appears largely in the variety of [[species]] and other [[taxa]] below the level of [[order (biology)|order]]. "The spectacular radiation of the [[angiosperm]]s, [[mammal]]s and certain [[reptile]] groups (such as the snakes) on land is matched by that of the planktonic [[foraminifera]], neo[[gastropods]], heteroconch [[bivalve]]s, [[Cheilostomata|cheilostome]] [[bryozoan]]s, [[Decapoda|decapod]] [[crustacean]]s and [[teleost]] fish in shallow seas."<ref>page 5 in {{cite book|author=Owen AW & Crame JA|chapter=Palaeobiogeography and the Ordovician and Mesozoic-Cenozoic biotic radiations|pages=1–11|editor=Crame JA and Owen AW|series=Geological Society Special Publications|number=194|title=Palaeobiogeography and Biodiversity Change: the Ordovician and Mesozoic-Cenozoic Radiations|location=London|publisher=[[Geological Society of London|The Geological Society]]|year=2002|isbn=1-86239-106-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Hallam A|authorlink=Anthony Hallam|title=An Outline of Phanerozoic Biogeography|series=Oxford Biogeography|number=10|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1994|isbn=9780198540618}}</ref> The marine diversification is largely that represented by the modern [[evolutionary fauna]], and there are also the terrestrial diversifications of the [[bird]]s and among the [[insect]]s.

